Md.Des: Staying in the Verdanhs Hostel we had a few days to explore Auckland while getting over the gruelling 31 hour flight.
After quickly exploring Auckland we found ourselves across the harbour in Devonport.
Venturing from the Auckland port we spent the day on Waiheke, long beaches and hidden vineyards. The island was incredible.
A quick trip to Piha to see the black sand beach ended with us quickly bombing it up North to the East coast to run from the rain. We weren't successful...
Continuing north we went through Kerikeri, stopping in a car park about to go sight see we stumbled upon car-park-roosters... 15-20 various roosters just freely roaming. Strange.
Going down the west coast we went into the Kauri forest to see the some of the largest Kauri trees, 1200-2000 years old!
Ironically named in the awful weather we stopped off at this hostel to have a break from the tent. In the morning we went searching for mussels along the coast.
Stopping off in Coromandel Town we treated ourselves to mussels for lunch, scallops for dinner and a couple of oysters in between.
Continuing round the Coromandel coast line we stopped off in Whitianga and hide from the rain in the Lost Springs.
Arriving at Hahei we had grand ideas for Cathedral Cove and Hot Water Beach, the rain had something else to say about that...
The sun! It's come back. With the tide also going out we went down to Cathedral Cove, the sea isn't even that cold!
After a quick stop in Hamilton for the night the next morning we shot straight over to Raglan ready to surf. To try surfing.
On the way to Raglan to attempt surfing, stopping off at a brilliant waterfall first.
Waiheke, it's easy to understand the hype behind this island when the sun comes out and you are standing on the beach.
Being in New Zealand you can't really miss seeing where the Hobbits came from...
Heading into Rotorua we decided to take a quick walk through a Red Wood park, at the end of the short trail was a fresh water spring; 15m deep pumping out two olympic swimming pools of water an hour.
Four times a day the dam opens it's gates to unleash the rapids through the valley to produce electricity, we decided to give it a watch. It's amazing how blue the water is!
All the pictures from the DSLR camera are untouched, no edits at all. And still, look how blue the water is.
Driving down from the Waitomo caves to New Plymouth we stopped for some lunch as soon as we saw the sea, the view was just what we needed to break up the 198km road.

Corrupted by clouds again we decided to leave the mountain for another, hopefully, clearer day. Exploring the city however we found great graffiti, a huge wind wand and an odd bouncy bridge: Te Rewa Rewa.

As we drove to New Plymouth we saw the amazing snowy cap of this mountain, unable to keep away we ventured up it. Not reaching the top, we certainly didn't have the gear, but we got to a pretty good vantage point!
Round and round you go up the spiral stair case to find yourself looking over all of Wanganui.
After a month in New Zealand we've made it to the end of the North island. For a place notoriously cloudly we where given beautiful sun to enjoy and explore Wellington.
Voyaging over the Cook Strait we are leaving the North Island behind and heading to the South with all of it's fjords and sounds.
A quick stop in Nelson to stretch our legs allowed us to take in some of the stunning views it had to offer.
Hiring a kayak for the day we ventured into the Abel Tasman National Park to find beautiful beaches and an island covered in seals.
We had to stop midway of our quick trip to Takaka to take in the view. That and to take a breather from the bending roads...
A huge natural water spring, pumping out 14,000 litres of water a second. More amazing for us, it's colour, visibility through this water is up to 60m.
Venturing just slightly into the Abel Tasman in complete darkness allowed for a few fantastic shots of the sky.
The best way to improve a long car journey is to pick up a stranger and visit lots of winerys.
Kaikoura without the stunning views and in the rain. At least the seals are happy!
Kaikoura in the sunshine. An improvement from the rain a day before, more seals came out and fantastic views all around.

Rushing from the east coast to west it was quite enjoyable to take a couple of days to rest and take in the very small village of Punakaiki, the 'pancake' rocks and plan our descend down the west coast.
Across seemingly the most of the west coast of New Zealand is drift wood. From the surf highway to here, beaches and beaches of drift wood.
Not one picture on this site has been edited. So believe just how thick and milky blue this water looked!
With a tip to go in the evening when the cloud is supposed to fade and the people disperse we headed up to Franz Josef Glacier, the valley walk was incredible with a wall of ice at the end.

New Zealand has a lot of wildlife, and a LOT of birds. Here is one of our favourites, the Pukeko, with a couple of chicks. These things just strut around all day not really seeming to care about the world around them.
Just down the road from Franz Josef is another glacier, Fox. Missing the rain only by seconds we had a good view from the top of a precarious path.
Our last night at Sir Cedrics Glow Worm hostel had us watching a group practice their fire antics.
Hiking back to Franz Josef after dark was eerie, there was nothing around apart from the odd possum every 600m, the view however was amazing.

Not having done any multiple day hikes we decided it'd be a good idea to do the Welcome Flat hike, which takes two days, you walk 18km to a hut, and then 18km back the next day. It wasn't easy. It was hell! But... Some of the sights to behold are pretty top notch.
A short video of the views we got to enjoy on the hellish hike!
Hiking up to Isthmus Peak only a few days after the Welcome Flat hike wasn't smart. But the view was stunning, seeing both lake Wanaka and Hawea
A fisheye panoramic view from 1386 metres above sea level seeing plenty of mountains and a couple of lakes.

Md.Tit: Catching Mt Cook At It's Best
Md.Des: Heading up to Mount Cook we got caught out by the cold cold rain and had to hide in an odd hostel for the day, the following day we got these views - worth the wasted day.

We had a few days in Queenstown, we did the Nevis Swing, we drank and we ate. Fergberger and a list of happy hours, it was pretty perfect. Just before leaving we ventured up to take a quick look over it all for another New Zealand amazing view.
Getting to the very bottom of South Island we took the opportunity to see the start of the highway but more importantly to see how far away home and the South Pole were.
The true tip of New Zealand, Stewarts Island. Home to more Kiwi than man, but not just Kiwi, Blue Penguins - go down to the wharf around dusk to see them all coming in.

Md.Tit: When In New Zealand, Bird Watch
Md.Des: Disclaimer: we aren't twitchers. But when you're in New Zealand you can't help but get carried away seeing all the birds. So when visiting Ulva Island and walking the small 4km track, it's hard not to get excited by so many different kind of birds mingling around you.
This place was incredible; 140m deep water running inside sheer cliff faces, seals, dolphins and a penguin. We couldn't have been luckier with the beautiful sun and relatively calm day.
Just as magnificient as Milford Sound, yet a lot bigger and for us: a lot wetter.
Head down to Curio Bay an hour before sunset and you'll see one of the rarest penguins slowly coming ashore. This yellow-eyed penguin loved playing up for all the spectators cameras.
If there is something New Zealand doesn't have to worry about running out of, it's waterfalls. A quick trip along the coast of the Catlins took us to the McLean Falls.
A quick stop on the way to Dunedin let us play around with... You guessed it, yet another waterfall!

A quick daring drive along a gravel road, bits being redone from the obvious loss of road throughout the winter leads you to a lighthouse high up on the cliff; a beautiful view and a New Zealand must do when in the South.

Heading off to Harrington point we went in search of the Albatross, sadly we didn't want to spend $50 each to see them. Instead we got a good view in the sun, swarms of seagulls attacking cars and seals playing in the water.

On the outskirts of Dunedin is a quick downhill walk, it only takes 5 minutes. Walking back up however, that takes 20. It's steep, and with good reason you start at the top of the cliff and end up through a tunnel at the end on a little cove.

11 Weeks it's taken us to explore New Zealand and now we've reached the end of the line: Christchurch. A city in rebuild, towering buildings abandoned for good reason covered in graffiti meet towering shipping containers, rubble and endless building work surrounded by new green patches - it's a city unlike any other in New Zealand with plenty to explore, the quakes certainly couldn't shake the charm from this place.

Riding the elevator up you'll find a restaurant at the top of the Sofitel in Melbourne which boasts an amazing view, more terrifying however if you aren't so keen on heights - the toilet has a floor to ceiling glass window, not the place to get caught with your pants down on a stormy day in my opinion...
Tucked away down almost every lane you can find a world of street art, Hosier and Acdc lane are just a couple of the busiest!
You'll find plenty of beaches around Melbourne, but where to start... For us, the nice quiet surf beach of Jan Juc with golden sands, clear water and the sun shining all day long.

Mt. Buffalo, a popular challenge for cyclists to ride up just to stream back down again. At the top you'll find a hotel in disrepair and an awesome view looking out onto other mountains hazed in blue.
1800m up in a ski resort, you'd expect snow to be on the ground and the ski lifts rotating away: not with the Australian summer underway, it's 25 degrees in the Australian Alps!
Over the mountains and back to the coast, staying a night in Lakes Entrance gave us the chance to see all the pelicans chilling amongst the seagulls.

Taking the huge ferry journey over to Raymond Island (200 metres...) we where given a chance to find Koala's in the wild, not a hard task at all, they littered the trees just hanging around looking unaware.
Exploring more of Melbourne we ended up on Brighton Beach; with haze around the big sky rises and flying foxes in the evening it wasn't quite the same as home!
An impressive but relatively empty place, especially for a capital of such a large country.
A quick stop for fuel on the way to Sydney allowed us the chance to gaze upon the very large and very odd Big Merino.
When in Sydney, do the New Year. Enjoying the evening on a boat in the harbour, taking in the skyline and fireworks. Happy New Year to all!
Walking from Bondi to Bronte and back again, a nice walk completely covered in people! A very popular walk obviously due to some fantastic beaches when the sun shines bright.
Taking the day to explore Sydney and some of it's major sites.
Walking around and hearing rustling from the trees around - Australia, like New Zealand offers a wide range of wildlife that always attracts the camera.
On top of Sydney, a huge eye in the sky allowed us to see a perfect panoramic view. Also, it's very, very high up...

Most days this market is rammed with people, so when they put the night market on during the summer months with good food, drink and a bit of souvenir shopping while a band plays it's no surprised the place is rammed! With a good view of the city high above it's certainly a place to visit.
Towards the start of the Great Ocean Road is the small seaside town of Lorne, and in it, the most beautiful array of bird life. Got food? They'll be your best friend if you have!
The Twelve, or is it Seven, Six, Five, I think I can see Eight? Apostles.

Loc.Des: Twelve Apostles, Great Ocean Road, Aus

Md.Des: Spread across the CBD White Night is a 7pm-7am art show. Jumping on a tram and exploring at 3am with crowds and crowds of people is a rather odd feeling, not to mention half the buildings coloured in.
As the sun sets the view from Albert Park looking out across Melbourne's CBD area is quite impressive, mainly due to the Eureka Tower that catches the sun and everyone's eye.

Head down to Phillip Island if you want a literal parade of little blue penguins to come in just after the sun sets; as soon as that sun goes down they don't let you keep your camera out but imagine groups of 10-30 penguins making a mad dash from the shore line to the top of the beach.
The Grand Prix being held in Melbourne only 50m from our flat... Safe to say it was a pretty loud weekend.
With a short break in Eden the sun came right out and the Kangaroos decided it was time for some golf.
Driving to Adelaide and back down the Great Ocean Road we had a second chance to visit Lorne, a well deserved place to stop.
Shame it wasn't a clearer day, the view of Melbourne was still impressive though!
Melbourne from another angle, visiting the Mornington Peninsula.
Well, they aren't easy to find, so we had to go to the sanctuary to see the Platypus. Completely worth it.
With just a week left in Melbourne it was time to go up the skydeck. What a place to live for six months! You can see our flat from up here...
Our first stop, the Grampians - we've done the Great Ocean road so it was time to see more of Victoria as we headed to Kangaroo Island.
Having missed them in New Zealand we snapped up the chance to watch the whales in Warrnambool messing around.

Where to start; we explored this amazing island in South Australia, worked on a farm that's trying to return to bushland and from it helped a koala into a new tree. An island strongly looked over, and not to be missed.
Moving on from Adelaide we set off into the outback, our first stop camping we where welcomed by Emu's and Kangaroo.
Driving up the outback getting towards the Northern Territory the landscape just becomes more and more orange.
It's huge, it's fantastic and pictures don't do it justice... The transitioning Uluru photos are taken about 15 minutes apart at sunset just to show the colour shift.
On the way back from Uluru it's hard not to turn off and stop over at Kings Canyon to take in the impressive site.

Getting to Alice Spring felt like arriving to an oasis, phone signal and grass, two things not to take for granted. A quick morning trip had us exploring the Standley Chasm along the MacDonnell Ranges
Continuing on the Stuart Highway we stopped to look at rocks, lots of big, round, rocks.
A large pool of water, it feels like it's heated but it's not. The ground is just warm enough to keep it at a constant 33 degrees; watch out for crocodiles...
Katherine kayaking down Katherine Gorge, in Katherine NT.
A gem just north of Katherine, the short but gruesome 2km walk in 38 degree heat to the upper pool is well worth it.
That's it, the Stuart Highway start to finish driven. Starting in Melbourne we've made it all the way up to Darwin, and even sold the car, bye Henry.
For the next five weeks our local is a surf club, coastal reserve, cafe, bar. A nice way to spend the weekend, even if the sand does burn your feet.
Who could visit the East Coast and not snorkel or dive the Great Barrier Reef? We visited a little part of it called Hastings Reef.
On the road again and heading North to find crocs and rainforest we took a short break at the aptly named Palm Cove.
A small yacht filled town on the way up to the Daintree, probably better to visit if you have yacht money, ok for backpackers...
Going up and down the Daintree we found a big Croc called Scarface, the alpha of the river, 4.5m long, almost as long as our boat, 700kg of muscle just drifting along beside us.

We made it all the way up to Cape Trib for another reef tour, supposed to be the best one too, but it's the rainy season and a front came in, with 2-3m waves our dingy couldn't set off and we were stuck on wet-land, found a boardwalk of crabs though...
Wild Platypus, almost impossible to photograph, quick little darting guys, follow the bubbles and you'll see them surface soon.
I wouldn't want to get on the wrong side of that fella, sitting chilling watching the waterfall we took our pictures and headed back on the road.
Leaving Australia we've made our way to Indonesia to look for Monkeys, Dragons, Manta Rays and everything else along the way.
Visit the Monkey Temple and watch monkeys steal peoples sunglasses in return for bananas, then watch tourists pay for there glasses back - a real good watch..!
In search for some Komodo Dragons we left Bali for the Island of Flores, right next to the Komodo National Park.
Big lazy lizards hanging around the kitchen, they might be lazy but don't get bitten by them, you won't have long left.
If you look hard enough you can see from the shore why it gets its name, but don't be fooled, it's not pink that's the camera trickery. Under the water though is coral and lots and lots of Nemo's.

Hiking Padur in the early morning seems like a cool idea, but it was hot. The four of us Brits up the hike looked more like puddles than people by the end of it. But the view was incredible showing off three bays, one with white sand, one with black and another pink (barely pink).

On the edge of the open ocean and another bay we all jumped from the boat and went snorkelling, all around us getting cleaned and drifting in the current Manta Rays, we thought they might be hard to find but one after another they kept coming.
Swimming around the Gili Islands the thing to do is find turtles, we finally found one and followed this fella for a good 15 minutes while he chilled and munched.
Being in Bali with the volcano eruption looming we had to take some pictures, the islands are deadly quiet but with nothing to fear we sat back and watched.
Who knew the ducks loved the rice paddies?..
Scattered across Bali are lots of temples, hiding from the mad roads and scooters they're worth taking the time to explore.
